Farmers need five things to succeed: good land, good seeds, farming supplies, time, and know-how.

Patricia, a farmer I met in Malawi, had barriers standing between her and every one of those things simply because she was a woman. But she overcame them. I wrote about her story in The #MomentofLift.

node.text:
Since COVID-19 emerged, I’ve been thinking about women I’ve met on my travels and how they’re doing. Can Patricia, a farmer in Malawi, still sell her crops when fewer people are gathering at the market? Does Christina, a teacher in Kentucky, have the tools to shift to remote learning? 

The pandemic has made the barriers these women face even more daunting. But it’s also an opportunity to build the better future they deserve.

Click the link in my bio to read our 2021 Annual Letter. m-gat.es/2KTNqE4

node.title: How to Make Sure Women are Not Left Behind Post-COVID

node.text:
2020 was the year global health went local.

COVID-19 brought home the fact that all of humanity is connected and diseases don’t care about borders.

The good news is: If we make sure the pandemic response reaches everyone, everywhere, we can create a world that’s healthier, more equal, and more resilient. 

Read more in this year’s Annual Letter. https://m-gat.es/2KTNqE4 

Link in my bio to learn more.

node.title: How We’ll Build a More Equal Post-COVID Future

node.text:
In 2014, my daughter Jenn and I stayed with a woman named Anna and her family in Tanzania. Anna told us about the small but courageous act that changed her life, her family, and her community.

Her story has stuck with me ever since. I wrote The #MomentofLift to share stories like Anna’s. I hope they inspire you like they’ve inspired me.

My parents taught me to leave the world better than I found it.

I know so many people across this country believe in giving back, too. Throughout the pandemic, Americans have shown up for each other in extraordinary ways.
 
In a year like no other, let’s make this a giving season like no other—starting with #GivingTuesday.

A great way to get involved is by using our foundation’s dedicated website, PowerOf.org, to find nonprofits in your community to support.
 
We all have the power to make a difference in someone’s life, and we can begin today.

I never thought I would get excited about mosquito bites. Then I met Dr. Adi Utarini.

In a groundbreaking experiment, she proved that inoculating mosquitoes with a bacteria called Wolbachia could help drive down rates of deadly dengue fever by preventing them from transmitting the disease.

I was proud to write about Dr. Utarini’s work for this year’s #Time100. I hope you find her as inspiring as I do.

node.text: If you know me, you know I love to read. That’s why one of my favorite parts of writing The #MomentofLift was connecting with fellow book lovers across the country. Two years later, I’m still grateful for the many conversations we shared about the power of women’s stories. Happy #NationalBookLoversDay to all my fellow bookworms. 📚

node.text: We’ve all heard that breastfeeding is the gold standard in infant nutrition, but we don’t hear often enough how challenging it can be for a mother: physically, emotionally, and logistically. This #WorldBreastfeedingWeek, let’s commit to finding new ways to support breastfeeding moms and make it easier for parents everywhere to nourish their babies. #WBW2021

node.text: I always love watching the Olympics. The #TokyoOlympics are particularly special because I get to cheer on my future son-in-law, @nayelnassar! We are so proud of you, Nayel (and Igor)!
